<section xml:id="sec_orthog_set_summ">
  <title>Summary</title>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        A subset <m>S</m> of <m>\R^n</m> is an orthogonal set if
        <m>\vu \cdot \vv = 0</m> for every pair of distinct vector <m>\vu</m> and <m>\vv</m> in <m>S</m>.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Any orthogonal set of nonzero vectors is linearly independent.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        A basis <m>\CB</m> for a subspace <m>W</m> of <m>\R^n</m> is an orthogonal basis if <m>\CB</m> is also an orthogonal set.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        An orthogonal basis <m>\CB</m> for a subspace <m>W</m> of <m>\R^n</m> is an orthonormal basis if each vector in <m>\CB</m> has unit length.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        If <m>\CB = \{\vv_1, \vv_2, \ldots, \vv_m\}</m> is an orthogonal basis for a subspace <m>W</m> of <m>\R^n</m> and <m>\vx</m> is any vector in <m>W</m>, then
        <me>
          \vx = \sum_{i=1}^m c_i \vv_i
        </me>
        where <m>c_i = \frac{\vx \cdot \vv_i}{\vv_i \cdot \vv_i}</m>.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        An <m>n \times n</m> matrix <m>P</m> is an orthogonal matrix if <m>P^{\tr}P = I_n</m>.
        Orthogonal matrices are important, in part,
        because the matrix transformations they define are isometries.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</section>